      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Philosophically, the concept of national sovereignty posits that a state possesses supreme and exclusive authority within its territorial borders, making border control a non-negotiable function of self-preservation. Legally, this is rooted in international law which grants states the inherent right to control entry and exit to maintain internal order and protect its populace. The \"rule of law\" argument dictates that any legal system requires predictable boundaries; failing to enforce these boundaries undermines the very legitimacy of the state's governance structure. Therefore, controlling who enters is not just a policy choice, but a fundamental assertion of governmental authority.",
      "source": "target",
